assemblage.p:
If x=f(t) and y = g(t) are the parametric equations for a curve C, then the derivative \dfrac{dy}{dx} is given by

	\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \dfrac{dy/dt}{dx/dt}

provided that dx/dt \neq 0

proof.p:
From the chain rule, 

	\dfrac{dy}{dt} = \dfrac{dy}{dx}\cdot \dfrac{dx}{dt}

Rearranging gives the desired quantity.

assemblage.p:
If x = f(t) and y = g(t) are the parametric equations for a curve C with derivative \dfrac{dy}{dx}, then the second derivative \dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} is given by

	\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = \dfrac{\dfrac{d}{dt}(dy/dx)}{dx/dt}

Provided that dx/dt \neq 0

solution.p:
If y = g(\theta) = r\sin\theta and x = f(\theta) = r\cos\theta, then f'(\theta) = -r\sin\theta. For the entire circle, we will use \alpha = 0\leq \theta \leq 2\pi = \beta. Then, we have
\ds \int_\alpha^\beta y\, dx \amp = \ds \int_0^{2\pi} (r\sin\theta)(-r\sin\theta)\, d\theta \amp = \ds -\int_0^{2\pi} r^2 \sin^2\theta\, d\theta \amp = \ds -r^2\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2\theta\, d\theta \amp = -r^2\lrpar{\ds \dfrac{1}{2}x - \dfrac{1}{4}\sin 2x}\bigg\rvert_0^{2\pi} \amp = -r^2\lrpar{\pi}
So we conclude the unsigned area is \pi r^2. Naturally, if we want the positive version, we could reverse the direction of the parametrization.
